  <div class="section">
    <h2>Top 3 Specific Changes</h2>

    <div class="change p0">
      <span class="priority p0">P0</span>
      <div><strong>No quantified problem or success criteria. The entire doc is directional adjectives.</strong></div>
      <div class="quote">"Improve engagement with notifications / Increase trust / Reduce noise"</div>
      <div>None of these are metrics. There is no baseline, no target, no measurement method, no timeframe. A VP cannot greenlight headcount against "improve engagement." Replace with: current notification CTR / opt-out rate, the specific delta you are committing to, and how you will measure it. If you do not have the baseline numbers, that gap is itself a finding to surface before this goes up.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="change p0">
      <span class="priority p0">P0</span>
      <div><strong>The evidence is asserted, not shown. Every claim is unsourced.</strong></div>
      <div class="quote">"we are seeing engagement decline" / "Early customer interviews show strong interest" / "Early customer feedback is positive"</div>
      <div>How much decline, over what period, in which segment? How many interviews, with whom, saying what? "Feedback is positive" on a solution you have not built yet is not possible and reads as wishful. A VP at high stakes will not fund an ML investment on three unsourced assertions. Cite the data or cut the claim.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="change p1">
      <span class="priority p1">P1</span>
      <div><strong>You jumped to ML as the solution without justifying it over cheaper options.</strong></div>
      <div class="quote">"We will build a smart routing system that uses machine learning..."</div>
      <div>Why ML and not user-configurable preferences, rule-based batching, or a simple frequency cap? Those are far cheaper and a VP will ask why you skipped them. The doc presents the most expensive solution as the only one considered. Add the alternatives you rejected and why, or you look like you reached for ML because it is fashionable.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>By-Lens Findings</h2>

    <details open>
      <summary>Lens 1: The Skeptic</summary>
      <div class="lens-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Unsubstantiated decline.</strong> "engagement decline" has no number, period, or segment.</li>
          <li><strong>Impossible evidence.</strong> "Early customer feedback is positive" listed under success metrics for an unbuilt system. You cannot have feedback on a thing that does not exist. This is conflating problem-validation interest with product validation.</li>
          <li><strong>Suppress is a dangerous verb.</strong> "decide which notifications to surface, suppress, or batch." Suppressing notifications has real risk: a missed security alert, a dropped payment failure, a legal-mandated notice. The doc never addresses what must never be suppressed. This is the strongest opposing argument and it is absent.</li>
          <li><strong>"significantly reduce noise and improve user satisfaction"</strong> stated as a certainty before any build. Circular: the success criteria assume the outcome.</li>
          <li><strong>No counter-case.</strong> What if routing reduces engagement with high-value notifications users actually wanted? Not addressed.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Lens 2: The Audience (VP Product)</summary>
      <div class="lens-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>First sentence buries nothing because there is nothing to bury.</strong> A VP wants the size of the prize up top: how many users affected, revenue or retention at stake. Currently the problem statement could describe any product at any company.</li>
          <li><strong>Immediate questions left unanswered:</strong> What is the cost of inaction? What is the expected ROI? What does "smart" mean concretely? What is the failure mode? None are in the doc.</li>
          <li><strong>"roughly one quarter, depending on prioritization"</strong> tells a VP nothing actionable and signals you have not scoped it. This phrasing invites the VP to deprioritize it.</li>
          <li><strong>"some ML infrastructure help"</strong> is not a resource ask. A VP allocates against specifics: how many engineers, for how long, whose roadmap moves.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Lens 3: The Strategist</summary>
      <div class="lens-body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No point of view.</strong> The doc summarizes a problem and names a technology. It never argues why this is the right bet now versus other things the team could build.</li>
          <li><strong>Punting via "depending on prioritization."</strong> You are asking the VP to make the call you should be making. Own the recommendation: this is worth a quarter because of X, here is what we deprioritize to do it.</li>
          <li><strong>No clear ask.</strong> What decision do you need from this VP? Approval? Headcount? A trade-off sign-off? The doc ends without asking for anything.</li>
          <li><strong>List-heavy, no narrative.</strong> Success metrics are four bullets with no story connecting problem to outcome.</li>
          <li><strong>No scope boundary.</strong> What is explicitly out of scope for v1? Absence makes this look unbounded, which reads as risky to fund.</li>
        </ul>
